CALL FOR PAPERS SOL 2000 - - - - - - - - - - - - Workshop on Supporting Organisational Learning : Knowledge Management and Case-based Reasoning http : / / www . ifcomputer . co . jp / sol 2000 / Introduction - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - The only competitive advantage of the dynamic future is an organisation 's ability to learn - create ideas and move them into the marketplace profitably and expeditiously . An organisation ability to manage knowledge must be at the heart of a strategy to create distinctive competencies , unique market positioning and sustained growth over time . It is usually not that organisations are at a loss for ideas , but rather they lake the infrastructure to move ideas to prosperity . Convergence across technologies , across industries and across functions is accelerating the momentum of knowledge management . Knowledge has become the most important resource in many organisations . The success of an organisation depends on its ability to transform the personal knowledge of its employees into organisational knowledge . Organisational knowledge is reflected in processes , people management and information flow within the organisation . To achieve this goal , several ways to implement knowledge are introduced . Most approaches take a given viewpoint as starting point . People management , information management and process management are often the focus of knowledge solutions . Although these different views appear to be contradicting and conflicting with each others they aim at a common objective : that of supporting organisations in their learning efforts leading to sustainable advantage in a society where knowledge is the main asset . Objectives - - - - - - - - - - - - - Tremendous technological changes are forcing businesses and institutions to reorganise in order to achieve sustainable advantage . This requires altering mechanisms and processes in organisations , creating new ways of learning and managing knowledge . The purpose of this workshop is to bring together researchers and practitioners working on Organisational Learning , Knowledge Management , Case-based Reasoning and topics relating to the integration of these fields . Our goals are to encourage and review progress on integrating these fields and especially discuss ideas towards further integration . SOL 2000 provides an international forum for presentation and discussion of research and recent technological advances on knowledge management and learning organisations . The purpose of the workshop is to identify and discuss challenging problems facing the future of organisations in the upcoming knowledge economy , and to discuss and shape future directions of research challenges and initiatives . The workshop is intended to outline the major trends - established , emerging and over the horizon and define the core premise fundamental to a collaborative future of integrated and structural approach to enterprise knowledge . SOL 2000 is a workshop , not a conference , and the objective is to promote the exchange of ideas on innovative research through extensive discussion . Authors should aim to generate discussion on issues concerning knowledge management and learning organisations , rather than describe their research in detail . Full papers will be available in the web in advance in order to allow participants to prepare their comments in advance . Topics of interest include , but are not limited to the following areas : * Tools , frameworks and methods for Knowledge management * Logic programming and knowledge management * Business decisions and Knowledge discovery * Distributed knowledge management * Intranet and internet solutions for Knowledge Management * Technologies for learning organisations * Virtual learning and web-based training * Multimedia Knowledge representation * Market Intelligence Systems * Business Intelligence * Formal and informal knowledge in KM and CBR * Knowledge sharing * CBR research on lessons learned systems * Maintenance of large case bases as a knowledge management problem * Comparison of approaches * Discussions on the limitations of using CBR ( KM ) for KM ( CBR ) tasks Submission details - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - Submissions are not limited to traditional research papers . Position and survey papers pertaining to this subject are particularly encouraged as well as promising preliminary research . Also accepted are Industrial Reports and demonstrations . This type of submission is intended for the presentation of real-life ( industrial ) applications . Submission and review of papers , and co-ordination of all aspects of the meeting , will be through the Internet . Draft papers ( in HTML or PDF format only ) should be mailed to Virginia Dignum at v . dignum @ mat . bbd . dv ( See Important dates for deadlines ) . Accepted submissions will be published in the Web and included in the workshop proceedings . At least one author of each accepted paper is expected to attend the workshop . The format of presentations is as follows : 10 minutes for presentation and 20 minutes for discussion . Information for authors - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - Length limitations for papers are ( A 4 pages ) : full papers should have a maximum of 8 pages , position papers should be a maximum of 2 pages and research abstracts should be 1 page . Please include a cover page including : 1 . Full contact details 2 . A short abstract 3 . A list of keywords 4 . A brief statement of your interests in this topic . Authors who submit papers to the workshop will be expected to help with the refereeing of papers submitted by other individuals . Reviews are due by 30 June 2000 .
